The feedpoint is usually at the center of the dipole as shown in the diagram. The current along dipole arms are approximately described as proportional to formula_4 where is the distance to the nearest end of the arm. In the case of a short dipole, that is essentially a linear drop from formula_5 at the feedpoint to zero at the end. Therefore, this is comparable to a Hertzian dipole with an &quot;effective&quot; current h equal to the average current over the conductor, so formula_6 With that substitution, the above equations closely approximate the fields generated by a short dipole fed by current formula_7

