If a half-wave dipole is driven at a point other the center, then the feed point resistance will be higher. The radiation resistance is &quot;usually&quot; expressed relative to the maximum current present along an antenna element, which for the half-wave dipole (and most other antennas) is also the current at the feedpoint. However, if the dipole is fed at a different point at a distance from a current maximum (the center in the case of a half-wave dipole), then the current there is not but only 

